article.headline: Beard leads Duke with 17 points with sprained ankle
article.linkText: Beard battles ankle injuries to lead Duke past FSU
article.story:
TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Alana Beard would just as soon not face Florida State during next week's Atlantic Coast Conference tournament.

The Duke star sprained her left ankle but still scored 17 points to lead the second-ranked Blue Devils past the Seminoles 70-49 Thursday night.

Beard, a junior guard, watched the final 7:41 of the game on the bench as the Blue Devils won their 39th straight ACC game. Beard also sat out three minutes in the first half after twisting her right ankle.

"The last time we played them, Beard was in foul trouble and
sat out the final 12 minutes of the game,'' Duke coach Gail
Goestenkors said. "I don't know if it's not meant for her to play
a whole lot against Florida State.''

In that Jan. 26 game, which Duke won 81-63, Beard had a season-low seven points, snapping her streak of 40 straight games in double figures.

She reached seven points in the first half Thursday night when she completed a three-point play, but it was Duke's supporting cast that did all the damage in a decisive 13-0 run.

Duke (27-1, 15-0 ACC), which hadn't trailed at any point in six games, traded leads four times in the first five minutes. Florida State (15-11, 7-8) connected on its first five shots and led 14-13 after a pair of free throws from Holly Johnson. The Blue Devils regained the lead on Lindsey Harding's driving layup, then blew the game open with the 13-0 run.

Sheana Mosch scored four of her 13 points in the run, which
helped the Blue Devils take a 41-30 halftime lead. Duke enjoyed a
25-7 advantage in bench scoring and turned 24 Florida State
turnovers into 25 points.

Tasheika Morris had 18 points to lead Florida State, which has
lost six straight. The Seminoles couldn't gain ground on the Blue
Devils, despite limiting them to six second-half field goals.

Beard scored six consecutive points after the Seminoles pulled
to 45-36 to turn back the only threat.

   The only suspense in the second half came when Beard collapsed
in a heap following a collision on the baseline. "It was pretty
painful, but it wasn't like, 'Oh my God, I'm out for the season,''' Beard said.

With Beard hobbled and second-leading scorer Iciss Tillis
limited to eight points because of foul trouble, Duke turned to its
defense, which forced the Seminoles to missed 28 of its final 40
shots.

"This was a tough game, and we did have some adversity,'' Goestenkors said. "We always show great character through adversity.''
